  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 2.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Shemaiah the man of God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This is the first historical mention (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 12:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of Shemaiah. The second is found in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 12:5, 7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", on occasion of the invasion of Judah and Jerusalem by Shishak King of Egypt; and the third, in the same chapter, ver. 15, that he wrote a book respecting the acts of Rehoboam. The expression, \"man of God,\" owns to a somewhat unexplained history. It is first found in the added part of Deuteronomy (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 33:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), where it is applied to Moses. It occurs once in Joshua (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 14:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); twice in Judges (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 13:6, 8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); four times in Samuel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 2:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 9:6-8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "twenty-nine",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " times in Kings; six times in Chronicles; once each in Ezra, Nehemiah and Jeremiah. 2 Chronicles 11:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
